  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Business Manager Visa requires establishing your company in Japan before applying, which creates a chicken-and-egg challenge. Most applicants use a proxy (lawyer or judicial scrivener) to register the company, then apply for the Certificate of Eligibility (CoE), and finally obtain the visa from their home country embassy.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Develop Business Plan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Create a detailed business plan for the Japanese market. Include: executive summary, market analysis, revenue projections, use of funds, and why your business will succeed in Japan. This doesn't need to be in Japanese initially but shows you've done serious planning.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register Company in Japan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Work with a judicial scrivener (shiho shoshi) and/or lawyer to register your KK or GK. They can act as your proxy while you're still abroad. Deposit capital (¥5M+) into a Japanese bank—often challenging from abroad, but specialists can arrange this.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Secure Office Space</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Sign a commercial lease for your business premises. Cannot be a residential address or your future apartment. Your representative or lawyer in Japan may sign on behalf of the company. Take photos for the visa application.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Certificate of Eligibility (CoE)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Your representative in Japan submits the CoE application to the regional Immigration Bureau. Include: business plan, company registration documents, office lease, capital evidence, your resume, and photos. Processing: 1-3 months typically.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive CoE and Apply for Visa</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Once approved, the CoE is mailed to your representative in Japan, who sends it to you. Take the CoE to your local Japanese embassy/consulate, apply for the actual visa (quick process, 3-5 days typically), and receive your passport with visa.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Enter Japan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Enter Japan within 3 months of visa issuance. At immigration, present your CoE and visa. You'll receive a residence card (Zairyu Card) at the airport for 1-year initial status. Your Business Manager status begins.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register Residence and Enroll in Services</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Within 14 days: register address at city/ward office, receive residence certificate (juminhyo), enroll in NHI and National Pension. Open personal bank account (can be challenging—bring company documents). Get a phone number and set up utilities.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Startup Visa alternative:</strong> Some cities (Tokyo's Shibuya, Fukuoka, Kobe) offer a Startup Visa allowing 6-12 months to prepare before meeting full requirements. This lets you enter Japan first, find office space, refine your business plan, and then convert to Business Manager status. Ideal for entrepreneurs who need boots-on-ground preparation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

