  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse and children can apply for Dependent visas, allowing them to live in Japan. Spouses can work up to 28 hours/week without additional permission. Children can attend Japanese schools (excellent public education is free). Each family member needs their own health insurance enrollment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does it take to get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Standard path is 10 years of continuous residence. However, the Highly Skilled Foreign Professional (HSFP) points system can reduce this to 3 years (70+ points) or just 1 year (80+ points). Points come from education, work experience, income, and other factors. Many business owners qualify for accelerated PR.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Japanese citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, after 5 years of continuous residence, you can apply for naturalization. Requirements include: 5+ years residence, age 20+, good conduct, sufficient assets, renouncing other citizenship (Japan doesn't allow dual). Language ability is assessed. The process takes 6-12 months.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Japanese?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          It's not legally required for the visa, but business success often requires it. Some industries (IT, export/import to English markets) can operate in English. However, hiring, customer service, administrative tasks, and daily life are much easier with Japanese. Most successful business owners invest in learning.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your visa status depends on maintaining a viable business. If your business closes, you need to either: start a new qualifying business, change to a different visa status (work visa if you find employment), or leave Japan. Discuss contingency plans with an immigration lawyer before problems arise.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for other companies too?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your primary activity must be managing your business. However, with "Permission to Engage in Activities Other Than Those Permitted" (資格外活動許可), you can do limited additional work. Consulting for other companies or part-time work may be possible with proper permission.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Japan's Business Manager Visa offers a genuine path to building a business in one of the world's most developed economies. The ¥5M (~$33K) investment threshold is remarkably accessible—far lower than Singapore, Hong Kong, or Western alternatives. For entrepreneurs drawn to Japanese culture, markets, or lifestyle, this visa provides a legitimate route to residence and eventually citizenship.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are real: this is not a passive investment visa, Japanese business culture has a learning curve, and the language barrier is significant. The 10-year standard path to permanent residence is longer than European alternatives (though HSFP points can accelerate to 1-3 years). Office requirements add cost beyond the capital investment.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Healthcare is excellent and mandatory—NHI provides comprehensive coverage with manageable copays. Most expats find the Japanese healthcare system superior to their home countries. Optional private insurance adds international coverage and English support but isn't essential for medical care within Japan.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Japan's Business Manager Visa suits genuine entrepreneurs who want to build a business in Japan—not passive investors seeking a Golden Visa. Come with ¥5M+, a real business plan, commitment to active management, and willingness to embrace Japanese culture. The reward is life in one of the world's safest, most developed countries with a genuine path to permanent residence and citizenship.
      </p>
